<A NAME="Glossary"><H2>Glossary</H2></A>
<P>The following section describes the acronyms and terms used in the Browser Help.<P>

<DL><DT><B>AIFF</B><DD>Audio Interchange File Format. A sound file format.<P> 
<DT><B>AU/SND</B><DD>A sound file format.<P>
<DT><B>authentication</B><DD>A process which verifies that incoming messages were originated from their stated source.<P>
<DT><B>browser</B><DD>A program that lets you view HTML pages on the World Wide Web (WWW).<P>
<DT><B>cache</B><DD>A place in memory where the browser stores Web documents that have been retrieved.<P>
<DT><B>connection</B><DD>Communication between two <A HREF="#host">hosts</A>.  Usually one host sends data to another host.<P>
<DT><B>destination server</B><DD>A computer system that stores Web pages, usually at another site.  You can access the information stored on this server using a <A HREF="#url">URL</A>.<P>
<DT><B>E-Mail</B><DD>Electronic Mail.  A system for exchanging messages across computer networks.
<DT><B>Favorites List</B><DD>A list of URLs that you've saved.  A Favorites List lets you return to a favorite URL quickly and easily.<P>
<DT><B>form</B><DD>A Web document that contains fields into which you can enter information.<P> 
<DT><B>GIF</B><DD>Graphics Interchange Format.  An image file format.
<DT><B>HTML</B><DD>HyperText Mark-up Language.  A collection of tags used to mark blocks of text and assign formatting characteristics.<P>
<DT><B>History List</B><DD>A list of URLs that you've visited during the current session.  You can return to a URL by clicking on it in the History List.<P>
<DT><B>Home page</B><DD>The default Web page that appears when you start the browser program.<P>
<DT><B><A NAME="host">host</A></B><DD>A computer that's directly connected to the Internet.<P>
<DT><B>hypertext link</B><DD>A connection between two Web documents.  Can also be a shortcut to a destination within an HTML document.<P>
<DT><B>JPEG</B><DD>Joint Photographic Experts Group.  A compressed graphic format used for images on the WWW.<P>
<DT><B>MS WAV</B><DD>A sound file format.<P>
<DT><B>PNG</B><DD>Portable Network Graphics.  An image file format.<P>
<DT><B>Psion</B><DD>A pocket-sized computer produced by Psion, a UK company.<P>
<DT><B>server</B><DD>A computer system that provides file-handling and storage functions for multiple users.  Web pages are stored on servers.<P>
<DT><B>Sprite</B><DD>A small bitmap image.<P>
<DT><B>status line</B><DD>A text field located underneath the Browser Toolbar.  This field displays browser status and error messages.<P>
<DT><B>Toolbar</B><DD>A collection of buttons located across the top of the Browser screen.  Clicking on a button gives you access to browser functions.<P>
<DT><B><A NAME="url">URL</B><DD></A>Uniform Resource Locator.  An address used to locate Web pages.<P>
<DT><B>VOC</B><DD>Creative Voice Format.  Used with SoundBlaster products.<P>
<DT><B>World Wide Web (WWW)</B><DD>A hypertext-based system for accessing data over the Internet.<P>
</DL>

